05659nam a22007815i 9780812296143DE-B159720210621102733.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210621t20192019pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808122961437 a10.9783/97808122961432doi  a(DE-B1597)528755  a(OCoLC)1097973967  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aF12.C7bR63 2019 7aHIS0360202bisacsh04a9742231 aRoberts, Strother E., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aColonial Ecology, Atlantic Economy :bTransforming Nature in Early New England /cStrother E. Roberts. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2019] 4c©2019  a1 online resource (280 p.) :b8 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aEarly American Studies00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction. Conflicts, Choices, and Change -- tChapter 1. Hunting Beaver: The Postdiluvian World of the Fur Trade -- tChapter 2. Raising Crops: Feeding the Market -- tChapter 3. Gathering Firewood: Scarcity Amid Abundance -- tChapter 4. Felling Timber: Profits and Politics -- tChapter 5. Keeping Livestock: A Commerce in Beasts Domestic and Wild -- tEpilogue. A New Era in the Life of the River -- tNotes -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFocusing on the Connecticut River Valley—New England's longest river and largest watershed— Strother Roberts traces the local, regional, and transatlantic markets in colonial commodities that shaped an ecological transformation in one corner of the rapidly globalizing early modern world. Reaching deep into the interior, the Connecticut provided a watery commercial highway for the furs, grain, timber, livestock, and various other commodities that the region exported. Colonial Ecology, Atlantic Economy shows how the extraction of each commodity had an impact on the New England landscape, creating a new colonial ecology inextricably tied to the broader transatlantic economy beyond its shores.This history refutes two common misconceptions: first, that globalization is a relatively new phenomenon and its power to reshape economies and natural environments has only fully been realized in the modern era and, second, that the Puritan founders of New England were self-sufficient ascetics who sequestered themselves from the corrupting influence of the wider world. Roberts argues, instead, that colonial New England was an integral part of Britain's expanding imperialist commercial economy.Imperial planners envisioned New England as a region able to provide resources to other, more profitable parts of the empire, such as the sugar islands of the Caribbean. Settlers embraced trade as a means to afford the tools they needed to conquer the landscape and to acquire the same luxury commodities popular among the consumer class of Europe. New England's native nations, meanwhile, utilized their access to European trade goods and weapons to secure power and prestige in a region shaken by invading newcomers and the diseases that followed in their wake. These networks of extraction and exchange fundamentally transformed the natural environment of the region, creating a landscape that, by the turn of the nineteenth century, would have been unrecognizable to those living there two centuries earlier.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 7aHISTORY / United States / Colonial Period (1600-1775).2bisacsh  aAmerican History.  aAmerican Studies.  aEcology.  aEnvironmental Studies.  aMedieval and Renaissance Studies.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019 Englishz978311061076508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019z9783110664232oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe Gr